solutions.content:
`age_count[i]` is a accumulative number of people with age up to ` i`.
Example:
`age_count[1]` is the number of people of age 1
`age_count[2]` is the number of people of age 1,2
`age_count[3]` is the number of people of age 1,2,3
...
`age_count[120]` is the number of people of age 1,2,3,...,120

To find the requests a person can make, we find the age lower bound and upper bound according to the rules. Let's say the current person of the `age`.

age[y] <= 0.5 * age[x] + 7            => discard any one with age <= `0.5 * age + 7`
age[y] > age[x]                              => discard any one with age > `age`
age[y] > 100 && age[x] < 100     => this rule is satisfied if the second one is satisfied.

The firsst rule will form the lower bound and the second rule will form the upper bound.
Let's recall how sum range works with prefix sum. Suppose we have the following prefix sum:
```
0      l         r
.......a.........b
```
where 
`l` stands for running sum from source array [0..l],
`r` stands for running sum from source array [0..r],

then, `prefix[r] - prefix[l]` is the running sum from source array [l+1..r].

This fits perfectly into our scenario. Here 
`l` will be `0.5 * age + 7`
`r` will be `age` of the current person.

One edge case if when `0.5 * age + 7 > age`, there is no requests can be made.
It happens when age is < 14.


```
class Solution {
public:
    int numFriendRequests(vector<int>& ages) {
        // age_count[i] means the number of people with age <= i
        vector<int> age_count(121, 0);
        for(int age: ages)
            age_count[age]++;
        for(int i=2; i<=120; i++) {
            age_count[i] += age_count[i-1];
        }

        int requests = 0;
        for(int age: ages) {
            int left = age*0.5+7; 
            int right = age;
            if(left < right) {
                // -1 to excluse self
                requests += age_count[right] - age_count[left] - 1; 
            }
        }

        return requests;
    }
};
```

