solutions.content:
ages[A] >= ages[B] > ages[A] * 0.5 +7,
B has to be older than 14 to make the above equation valid.

There are two possible directions of requests after we sort ages int[]:
1. From upstream bigger or equal number to all people with age bigger than ages[A] * 0.5 +7.
2. From downstream to all people with same age upwards in the array

For No.1, one way to is to use binary search to find the lower bound, then add to result, but we can also just keep a pointer j to current upstream number, then keep going down. Since ages are sorted, and the lower bounder if a linear function of ages[A], before we process the higher ages[A] lower bound, we won't have to worry about missing other friend requests from other people with lower ages than A.
For No.2, we keep a state variable ageSame. Each time we find a j, lower j by 1, we compare and see if it has same age as last one, if same, sameAge++, if not, we reset it to 0. 
Lastly, after we break out of for loop, j needs to keep going down until it hits the end or someone with age under 15, with same logic as the for loop.
```
class Solution {
    public int numFriendRequests(int[] ages) {
        Arrays.sort(ages);
        int res = 0;
        int sameAge = 0;
        int curLowerBound = (int) (ages[ages.length - 1]/2) + 7;
        int j = ages.length - 1;
        int i = 0;
        for (i = ages.length - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (ages[i] < 15) break;
            while (ages[i] <= curLowerBound) {
                res += j - i - 1;
                j--;
                curLowerBound = (int)(ages[j]/2) + 7;
                if (ages[j] == ages[j+1]) {
                    sameAge++;
                    res += sameAge;
                } else sameAge = 0;
            }
        }

        while (j > 0 && ages[j] > 14) {        
            res += j - i - 1;
            j--;
            if (ages[j] == ages[j+1]) {
                sameAge++;
                res += sameAge;
            } else sameAge = 0;
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

