```   /**
     * O(n) solution
     * Thought: From  nlogn solution, the thing that cost most is the binary search to find the count of ages between lowerBound and upperBound
     * so the idea is to see whether we can reduce find counts from O(nlogn) O(1)
     *
     * since the total ages are between [1, 120]
     * so we can first use an array count the number of each ages O(n)
     *
     * for each age, we know there's a lowerBound and higherBound that ages[i] will send request
     * lowerBound = ages[i] / 2 + 8, upperBound = ages[i]
     * 
     * To calculate the count of ages between lowerBound and highBound in O(1), 
     * we use a prefixCount array
     * The count between age[upperBound] and age[lowerBound] will be
     * int count = prefixCount[i] - prefixCount[i / 2 + 7]; (prefixCount[i / 2 + 7] is exclusive)
     * then we can calcute the res for ages[i] by 
     * res += count * countAges[i] - countAges[i]; // people wont friend themselves
     *
     * @param ages
     * @return
     */
    public int numFriendRequestsII(int[] ages) {

        // total 120 possible ages in this question, use + 1 avoid overflow
        int[] countAges = new int[121];
       // prefixSum used to easy find out count of ages between lowerBound and higherBound
        int[] prefixCount = new int[121];
        for (int i : ages) {
            countAges[i]++;
        }
        for(int i = 1; i <= 120; i++) {
            prefixCount[i] = countAges[i] + prefixCount[i - 1];
        }

        int res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i <= 120; i++) {
            if(countAges[i] == 0) {
                continue;
            }
            if(i / 2 + 7 >= i) {
                continue;
            }
            int count = prefixCount[i] - prefixCount[i / 2 + 7];
            res += count * countAges[i] - countAges[i]; // people wont friend themselves
        }
        return res;
    }
```

