solutions.content:
Started solving this problem using DP, but then realized that the constraints are too large.

Then, I realized that, to reach `x`, we will take `l` numbers from the left, and `r` numbers from the right. We just need to find `min(l + r)`.

#### Approach 1: Hash Map
As you count the sum of the first `l` numbers, you need to find a complement `(x - sum)` number formed by numbers on the right. To do so, we can use a hashmap where we will store the rolling sum.
**C++**
```cpp
int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
    unordered_map<int, int> left;
    int res = INT_MAX;
    for (auto l = 0, sum = 0; l <= nums.size() && sum <= x; ++l) {
        left[sum] = l;
        if (l < nums.size())
            sum += nums[l];
    }
    for (int r = nums.size() - 1, sum = 0; r >= 0 && sum <= x; --r) {
        auto it = left.find(x - sum);
        if (it != end(left) && r + 1 >= it->second) {
            res = min(res, (int)nums.size() - r - 1 + it->second);
        }
        sum += nums[r];
    }
    return res == INT_MAX ? -1 : res;
}
```
#### Approach 2: Two Sum
> Note that this only works because we do not have negative values in the input array.

I got a feeling that this problem is a twisted variation of [Two Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/two-sum/). The rolling sum always increases, so we can use two pointers - both starting from one side - to find portions of the array that sum to `x`. 
**C++**
```cpp
int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
    int sum = accumulate(begin(nums), end(nums), 0);
    int l = 0, r = 0, res = INT_MAX, sz = nums.size();
    while (l <= r)
        if (sum >= x) {
            if (sum == x)
                res = min(res, l + sz - r);
            if (r < sz)
                sum -= nums[r++];
            else
                break;
        }
        else
            sum += nums[l++];
    return res == INT_MAX ? -1 : res;
}
```

