The idea is to find the length of the maximum length subarray that has a sum equal to ```sum(nums) - x```. This makes sense because after removing the optimal elements from the ends, this is what we will be left with. So instead of removing elements, add elements to this subarray in a sliding window fashion and optimize for the largest length of this subarray.

Example:
```nums = [1,1,4,2,3], x = 5```

sum = 11
req_subarray_sum = 11 - 5 = 6
The longest subarray with this sum is from index 0 to index 2 (1 + 1 + 4). This has length 3.
result = len(nums) - max_subarray_size = 5 - 3 = 2

```
class Solution:
    def minOperations(self, nums: List[int], x: int) -> int:
        arr_sum = sum(nums)
        if arr_sum < x:
            return -1
        if arr_sum == x:
            return len(nums)

        required_subarray_sum = arr_sum - x
        left = curr_sum = max_subarray_size = 0
        for right, num in enumerate(nums):
            curr_sum += num
            while curr_sum > required_subarray_sum:
                curr_sum -= nums[left]
                left += 1
            if curr_sum == required_subarray_sum:
                max_subarray_size = max(max_subarray_size, right - left + 1)

        return len(nums) - max_subarray_size if max_subarray_size > 0 else -1
```

