solutions.content:
Okay, I tried a number of approaches, including a 2d matrix for DP and a double-ended BFS, before realising that there was a much easier and performant solution; the tips for the problem definitely did not help.

The core idea is to compute and store all the partial sums from the left together with the indexes in which we can achieve them, then look for matches computing cumulative sums from the right, but I guess it will become clearer with some explanations.

First of all we declare a few support variables:
* `res`, our accumulator variable, initialised to `-1` (which will flag no valid solution was found);
* `len` will store the length of the vector;
* `tot` will store the partial sums;
* `m` is an `unordered_map` that we will use with partial sums as keys and indexes at which they were obtained as values.

We will then proceed and populate `m`; first of all we will have `0` obtained at the fictitious position of `-1`, that is to say: before even starting the sum, that is our initial value for it.

Looping from the left, we will compute the cumulative sum, store it in `tot` and store the matching index in `m[tot]`, as announced; we will loop as long as `i` is within the margins of our vector and `tot` is less than `x` (no point in proceeding further).

Once done, we have to deal with 2 edge cases:
* we run through the whole vector (`m[tot] == len - 1)`, so we return `len` if `tot == x` (ie: we need each single element to reach that value) or `-1` otherwise (ie: even summing them all, we cannot reach `x`);
* alternatively, if `tot == x`, it means that potentially we might proceed only removing from the left, but we do not return it yet, since removing from the right or a mix of the two might be even more convenient, so we just store `m[tot] + 1` (because we were storing `0`-based indexes) into `res` and move on with the second loop to check that.

We can now reset `tot == 0` and start computing a cumulative sum from the right. As soon as we find a matching key of `x - tot`, we update `res`, since it means that we might achieve `x` summing `tot` and, of course `x - tot`.

To update `res`, we check if a value of `res` was previously found (ie: `res > -1`), otherwise we take the top value `len` and then compute the minimum between it and the current one, found moving `m[tot] + 1` steps from the left (as explained above) and `len - j` steps from the right.

Once done, we can return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
        // support variables
        int res = -1, len = nums.size(), tot = 0;
        unordered_map<int, int> m;
        // storing the position of all the partial sums from left up to x
        // and relative indexes
        m[0] = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < len && tot < x; i++) {
            m[tot += nums[i]] = i;
        }
        // edge case: x >= the sum of all the elements in the vector
        if (m[tot] == len - 1) return tot == x ? m[tot] + 1 : -1;
        // edge case: x found just summing left numbers
        if (tot == x) res = m[tot] + 1;
        // resetting tot
        tot = 0;
        // moving on from the right
        for (int j = len - 1; j >= 0 && tot < x; j--) {
            // updating res if there is a match
            if (m.find(x - (tot += nums[j])) != end(m)) {
                res = min(res > -1 ? res : len, m[x - tot] + 1 + len - j);
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Micro-optimisation, you might find even more efficient to limit the second loop in some edge cases, when a viable `res` was already found and it does not make sense to parse from the right a long list of values relatively small compared to `x`:

```cpp

