# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem requires finding the minimum number of operations to reduce a given sum ‘x’ by removing elements from either end of the array. The goal is to find the maximum subarray that sums up to nums.Sum() - x.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1.	Calculate the total sum of the array (totalSum).
2.	Find the target sum by subtracting ‘x’ from totalSum.
3.	Use a sliding window approach to find the maximum subarray sum that equals the target sum.
4.	Keep track of the minimum length of subarray with the target sum.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity is O(n) where n is the length of the input array ‘nums’. The algorithm iterates through the array once using a sliding window approach.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) as we are using a constant amount of extra space, not dependent on the size of the input array. We only use a few integer variables to keep track of the window and the result.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int MinOperations(int[] nums, int x) {
        int targetSum = nums.Sum() - x;

        if (targetSum < 0)
            return -1;

        int leftSum = 0, rightSum = 0;
        int minLength = int.MaxValue;
        int left = 0, right = 0;

        while (right < nums.Length) {
            rightSum += nums[right];
            right++;

            while (rightSum > targetSum && left < nums.Length) {
                rightSum -= nums[left];
                left++;
            }

            if (rightSum == targetSum)
                minLength = Math.Min(minLength, nums.Length - (right - left));
        }

        return minLength == int.MaxValue ? -1 : minLength;
    }
}
```

