solutions.content:
# Brute Force

If we were to try brute force, we would perform a running sum from left to right. In each iteration of the running sum, we would try to find the corresponding sum adding up to x by running another running sum from right to left. 

This way would be O(N^2) time complexity, O(1) space complexity.

---

<br>

# Binary Search

* The intuition is that, we require extra information to reduce the time complexity. 
* If I already has the prefix sum array from left to right beforehand, then while performing a running sum from right to left, I can query the prefix sum array for the value required to add up to x in O(log N) time using binary search due to the fact that **prefix sum will be strictly increasing - sorted**.
* The overall time complexity will be then O(N log N), but extra space of O(N)

#### Java

```java
public int minOperations(int[] nums, int x) {
	final int len = nums.length;
	int cumulative = 0;

	//	Creation of Prefix Sum Array
	int[] prefixSum = new int[len + 1];
	for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i)
		prefixSum[i+1] = nums[i] + prefixSum[i];

	//	If we only pop from left side.
	int res = binarySearch(prefixSum, x);

	//	Start summing from the right side
	for (int i = 1; i <= len; ++i) {
		cumulative += nums[len - i];

		int search = binarySearch(prefixSum, x - cumulative);
		//	Invalid when: 1. Not found 2. Required range overlap with right subarray
		if (search == Integer.MAX_VALUE || search >= len-i ) continue;
		//	Otherwise a valid value! Record
		res = Math.min(res, i + search);
	}

	return res == Integer.MAX_VALUE? -1: res;
}

private int binarySearch(int[] prefixSum, int val) {
	int left = 0, right = prefixSum.length - 1;

	while (left < right) {
		int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
		if (prefixSum[mid] < val) 
			left = mid + 1;
		else
			right = mid;
	}

	return prefixSum[left] == val? left: Integer.MAX_VALUE;	//	Returns INF if not found
}
```

#### CPP

```cpp
int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
	const int len = nums.size();
	int cumulative = 0;

	//	Creation of Prefix Sum Array
	vector<int> prefixSum(len + 1, 0);
	for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i)
		prefixSum[i + 1] = nums[i] + prefixSum[i];

	//	If we only pop from left side.
	int res = binarySearch(prefixSum, x);

	//	Start summing from the right side
	for (int i = 1; i <= len; ++i) {
		cumulative += nums[len - i];

		int search = binarySearch(prefixSum, x - cumulative);
		//	Invalid when: 1. Not found 2. Required range overlap with right subarray
		if (search == INT32_MAX || search > len - i) continue;
		//	Otherwise a valid value! Record
		res = min(res, i + search);
	}

	return res == INT32_MAX ? -1 : res;
}

int binarySearch(vector<int>& prefixSum, int val) {
	int left = 0, right = prefixSum.size() - 1;

	while (left < right) {
		int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
		if (prefixSum[mid] < val)
			left = mid + 1;
		else
			right = mid;
	}

	return prefixSum[left] == val ? left : INT32_MAX;
}
```

<br>

# Binary Search to HashMap

* In binary search, at the end of the search, if the value at left pointer is not equal to the desired search value, it will return a invalid flag to indicate the value is not found.
* Then, realize that instead of searching for a specific value in prefix sum array using binary search, why not store all possible prefix sums into the HashMap where the length of the subarray is the value?
* This way time complexity is further reduced to O(N) but still same space complexity of O(N)

<br>

# Two pointers, Sliding window

* The intuition is, when performing running sum, the sum must be strictly increasing. The required counterpart to sum up to x must be strictly decreasing then.

* This idea came across when I am thinking about a Stack solution storing the prefix sums
* Perform running sum from left to right. Running sum is stored in `lSum`. If `lSum` matches `x`, record the length. Sum until the end of array.
* We would have two pointers `lPt` and `rPt`. `lPt` point at the tail of the left part of array. `rPt` will point at the head of the right side of array. After the above running sum, `lPt` will be at the end of array since we essentially summed everything from index 0 to n-1.
* Then, we would start another running sum from right to left. In each iteration, we will run a loop to retract the range of left array covered if needed:
	* If left pointer overlap with right pointer - Eg `leftPt` at n-1 and `rPt` also at n-1 when the running sum just started
	* If the sum covered by left array is too large, that is `lSum > x - rSum` 

* Once retracting process is done, it is either the `lSum` is less than or equal to the required value to add up to x, or `lPt` had hit index -1 (Left array exhausted)
* Check if `lSum` is now having the required value or not. If yes, record the length of left and right array combined.

#### Java

```java
public int minOperations(int[] nums, int x) {
	final int len = nums.length;
	int res = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
	int lSum = 0, lPt = len-1;

	//	Fill up to the right first
	for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
		lSum += nums[i];
		if (lSum == x) res = i+1;
	}

	int rSum = 0; 
	//	Filling up to the left, while attempting to search left cumulative.
	for (int i = len - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
		rSum += nums[i];

		//	If left pointer overlaps, or left sum is still exceeding, retract
		while (lPt == i || (lPt >= 0 && lSum > x - rSum) ) {
			lSum -= nums[lPt];
			--lPt;
		}

		//	Check leftsum
		if (lSum == x - rSum )
			res = Math.min(res, lPt + 1 + len - i);
	}

	return res == Integer.MAX_VALUE? -1: res;
}
```

#### C++

```cpp
int minOperations(vector<int>& nums, int x) {
	const int len = nums.size();
	int res = INT32_MAX;
	int lSum = 0, lPt = len - 1;

	//	Fill up to the right first
	for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
		lSum += nums[i];
