solutions.content:
The question states that we need to pick one element from each row , such that 
the absolute differnce b/w the sum  and target is minimized. In other words, their sum should be close to target.

Simple approach is try all possible combinatoins /paths, return the minimum value of abs(target-sum).
Here , our result does not depend upon which column we are landing in. It depends upon the row to be traversed , and the target remaining / or say sum of chosen values upto that row.

So , let f(row, sum) be a function, which determines the total sum of chosen elements (one from each row) upto row th row from last row.

f(row, sum)= min of( f(row-1, sum'), f(row-1, sum'').........)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1912072e-f0da-4494-9345-afbfdc10c49a_1644347575.3780317.jpeg)

The above diagram shows that we ahve overlapping subprobelms , hence optimization can be done using dp.

**Base case**- When row becomes 0 , that means we have included values from all rows to sum , hence we will return absolute difference of sum and target.

**Points to remember**- Since the dp array , has row of mat as its row , so max size of row can be m+1, but the columns of dp array is sum , and the maximum value of sum can be 70*70 , hence we will initialise dp[m][4900+1]


```
int minDiff(int row,int n, vector<vector<int>>&mat, int target,int sum,vector<vector<int>>&dp){
    if(row==0)return dp[0][sum]=abs(target-sum);

    if(dp[row][sum]!=-1)return dp[row][sum];
    int diff=INT_MAX;
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        int curr=minDiff(row-1,n,mat,target,sum+mat[row-1][i],dp);
        if(curr==0)return dp[row][sum]=0;
        diff=min(diff,curr);
    }
    return dp[row][sum]=diff;
} 
