Here is yet another tribute to my idol @lee215

Intuition:
1. Think of it similar to 0-1 knapsack problem. Here, the difference is that you have to choose one column in every row in this case and you have to choose an element.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int minimizeTheDifference(vector<vector<int>>& mat, int target) {
        vector<int> dp(target + 1);
        int m = mat.size(), n = mat[0].size();

		// base case: If number of rows is zero, target is your min abs diff.
        for (int i = 0; i <= target; i++) {
            dp[i] = i;
        }

        for (int k = 0; k < m; k++) {
            for (int i = target; i > 0; i--) {
                dp[i] = numeric_limits<int>::max();
                for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
					// for every column, if value <= i, min abs diff after choosing value will
					// be min(min abs diff of last row with target (i - value), min abs diff found
					// till now), otherwise it will be (value - i) + min abs diff of last row with target 0. 
					// This is done to ensure that the abs diff is minimum. 
                    dp[i] = min(dp[i], mat[k][j] <= i ? dp[i - mat[k][j]] : (mat[k][j] - i + dp[0]));
                }
            }
			// This is handled separately to handle integer overflow for (mat[k][j] - i + dp[0])
            dp[0] = dp[1] + 1;
        }

        return dp[target];
    }
};
```

**Time and Space Complexity:**
Similar to 0-1 knapsack problem (which can be solved in O(n * k) time, O(k) space complexity), This can be solved in **O(m * n * target)** time, **O(k)** space.

