solutions.content:
If you try to solve this with Brute-force, the run time would be O(n^n), and you would always get TLE.

My optimization is still to add the nums row by row, however, use a set call "to_visit" to track the "valid" numbers that can be brought to the next row. The valid number will be **all nums smaller than the target** plus **the smallest number that is larger than the target.** The logic is as follows:

1. Every smaller number in the to_visit set plus the numbers in the next row may be closer to your target.
2. The smallest larger number could be the only candidate that will be close to the target after the operation with the next row.

Using the example 

[[1,2,3],[4,5,6],[7,8,9]]
13

what you get each time in to_visit will be
{1, 2, 3}
{5, 6, 7, 8, 9}
{12, 13, 14} (you can get 15,16,17,18, but they are not the smallest larger num, so you can disgard them, we only keep 14 here)

Once you finsh iteration through the matrix, you can find the closest value in the last to_visit set with time of O(target), in the worst case.

I guess...Overall time complexity O(target * n * n) ), 
as the worst case scenario what you need to add to the to_vist would be target * n numbers, and you may need to repeat it for n times.

Overall space complexity O(target), 
as you only need to maintain the to_visit set, which has worst case size of the target + 1
```
class Solution:
    def minimizeTheDifference(self, mat: List[List[int]], target: int) -> int:
        to_visit = {0}
        for row in mat:
            larger_val = math.inf
            temp = to_visit.copy()
            to_visit = set()
            for num in set(row):    
                for item in temp:
                    if num + item <= target:
                        to_visit.add(num + item)
                    else:
                        larger_val = min(larger_val, num + item)
            if larger_val != math.inf:
                to_visit.add(larger_val)
            ans = math.inf
        for i in to_visit:
            ans = min(abs(target - i),ans)
        return ans


```

